article.description: Katie Douglas scored 21 points, including the go-ahead jumper, as the Sun defeated the Charlotte Sting, 63-55, in a game between playoff contenders.
article.headline: Connecticut moves into 3-way tie for third in East
article.linkText: Douglas' 21 points paces Sun past Sting
article.story:
UNCASVILLE, Conn. (AP) -- Katie Douglas scored 21 points and hit
two free throws with 25.4 seconds left to seal the Connecticut
Sun's 63-55 win over the Charlotte Sting on Friday night.

Douglas also had five assists and five rebounds for Connecticut,
which kept its playoff hopes alive with the win and prevented
Charlotte from clinching one of the three playoff spots remaining
in the Eastern Conference.

Charlotte is in second place, a game in front of both
Connecticut and Cleveland. New York is a half-game behind the Sun
and the Rockers. The top four teams in each conference make the
playoffs.

"I think we did a good job," Sun coach Mike Thibault said.
"Defensively we were very good down the stretch."

The Sun (16-16) began the game with a 12-2 run, but the Sting
(17-15) battled back to tie the game at 24 with 3:04 left in the
first half and kept the game close until the Sun closed the game
with a 9-1 run in the final 3:30.

"I thought we did a better job of communicating the last couple
of minutes," Thibault said. "We guarded their shooters and made
them shoot under duress. I thought the other key for us were the
offensive rebounds down the stretch. We know what's at stake. We
just have to play and make good basketball plays."

Shalonda Enis led the Sting with 17 points, 14 in the first
half. Dawn Staley had 10 points and five assists. Both teams have
two games remaining.

"We want to stay positive," Enis said. "This game could have
easily went our way. In a game that close, there is no room for
mistakes."

Connecticut's Nykesha Sales scored 10 of her 15 points in the
second half and grabbed seven rebounds.

"It's a relief (to win), but as you can see, even though we
won, and it was our last home game, none of us were cheering,"
Sales said. "We still have a lot of work to do."

Taj McWilliams-Franklin added 13 points and six rebounds for the
Sun.
